narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Circuit design. Digital circuit design. RF frequency testing. Impedance matching theory/maximum power transfer.
Good chance to learn more about a topic that you don't know, and this could be almost anything.
Learned a ton... probably one of the most rewarding classes, but could be very demanding at times. You'll only get out what you put in.

I got to apply some of the digital signal processing concepts that I had learned in eeng 450 - applied digital signal processing. I actually learned a lot about programming DSP in C, which I wish I had done more of in the previous class. It was great to use a real DSP chip and learn about the troubleshooting and practical issues that go into that. I feel much more comfortable with pole-zero plots, frequency response, and phase response.
I learned how to do independent research and write up/present my results.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: A lot of freedom to do what you want, but hard to get guidance because everyone in EE is always so busy.
Great way to force yourself to solidify a lot/implement what you've been taught over the last 3-4 years. Yale needs more open project courses like this.
Hard to evaluate, as this is entirely dependent on the instructor.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Take it because it's a good chance to learn something knew that will make you a better engineer
Find something you're passionate about, find a way to build something that will target that passion. This can really be an awesome class.
Definitely take 472 if you have an interesting project that you want to work on! Be sure to take it seriously and put in the work. It can be a very rewarding experience.
Well, you really don't have a choice, do you?
